<b><font size="+2"><center>Logic</center></b>
<b><font size="+1"><center>Learning Plan 3</center></b>
<P>
<b><center>Propositional Logic(Examples)</center></b><font size="--">
<P>



<P>Consider the two propositions:</P>
<UL>
<P>p : London is the capital of Britain</P>

<P>q : Glasgow is the largest city in Scotland</P>
</UL>
<P>The <B>conjunction</B> of p and q is</P>
<UL>
<P>p <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#217;</FONT>
 q : London is the capital of Britain and Glasgow is the largest city in Scotland.</P>
</UL>
<P>As p and q are both true then p <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#217;</FONT>
 q is true.</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>
<B><P>Example 2</P>
</B>
<P>Consider the two propositions:</P>
<UL>
<P>p : Ayr is on the east coast</P>

<P>q : Glasgow is the largest city in Scotland</P>
</UL>
<P>The <B>conjunction</B> of p and q is</P>
<UL>
<P>p <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#217;</FONT>
 q : Ayr is on the east coast and Glasgow is the largest city in Scotland</P>
</UL>
<P>As p is false the conjunction p <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#217;</FONT>
 q is false. </P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>The <B>inclusive disjunction</B>  of p and q is :</P>
<UL>
<P>p <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#218;</FONT>
 q : Ayr is on the east coast or Glasgow is the largest city in Scotland, or both.</P>
</UL>
<P>The inclusive disjunction of p and q, p <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#218;</FONT>
 q is true if at least one of p and q is true.   As q is true then p <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#218;</FONT>
 q is true. </P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>
<B><P>Example 3</P>
</B>
<P>Consider the proposition:</P>
<UL>
<P>p : one share of ABC Company is worth £1.20</P>
</UL>
<P>The <B>negation</B> of p is:</P>
<UL>
<P><FONT FACE="Symbol">&#126;</FONT>
p : one share of ABC Company is not worth £1.20.</P>
</UL>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<B><P>Quantifier</P>
</B>
<P>A quantifier is a word or phrase which says how many.   </P>

<P>The quantifiers &quot;each&quot;, &quot;every&quot;, &quot;any&quot;, and &quot;all&quot; are interchangeable.</P>

<P>The quantifiers &quot;some&quot; and &quot;there exists&quot; are interchangeable.</P>

<B><P>Example 4</P>
</B>
<P>The following propositions have the same meaning:-</P>

<br>
<UL>
<LI>All men are intelligent.</LI>
<LI>Every man is intelligent.</LI>
<LI>Each man is intelligent.</LI>
<LI>Any man is intelligent.</LI></UL>

<br>

<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>The <B>negation</B> of the proposition</P>
<UL>
<P>p : All men are intelligent</P>
</UL>
<P>is:-</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<UL>
<LI><FONT FACE="Symbol">&#126;</FONT>
p : Some men are not intelligent.</LI></UL>
<DIR>

<P>or</P></DIR>

<br>
<UL>
<LI><FONT FACE="Symbol">&#126;</FONT>
p : There exists a man who is not intelligent.</LI></UL>

<br>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>The <B>negation</B> of the propositions:</P>
<UL>
<P>p : There is a man who is not intelligent.</P>

<P>p : Some men are not intelligent.</P>
</UL>
<P>is:-</P>
<UL>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P><FONT FACE="Symbol">&#126;</FONT>
p : All men are intelligent.</P>
</UL>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<B><P>Law of Contradiction</P>
</B>
<P>A proposition <B>and</B> its negation <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#126;</FONT>
p cannot be true.</P>

<P>This is the end of the third Logic Learning Plan.</P>

